In modern times and beyond, mechanical pumping of hot spring water began, resulting in major changes to how hot spring resources were utilized.<ref name="高柳" />

At {{ill|Asama Onsen|ja|浅間温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, for instance, both internal baths and communal baths (Sotoyu) existed as far back as the Edo period, and in the early Meiji period, the number of internal baths rose while communal baths also became more numerous.<ref name="井田">{{Cite journal |和書 |url=https://www.geoenv.tsukuba.ac.jp/~chicho/nenpo/7/08.pdf|author1=井田仁康 |author2=上野健一 |title=浅間温泉の形成過程と集落構造 |journal=地域調査報告 |volume= |issue= |publisher=筑波大学 |date=1985|pages=|naid= |ref=}}</ref> This led to the development of a system of “bath share certificates,” giving rise to three types of external communal baths: those used only by certificate holders, those open to general users upon payment of a bathing fee, and those managed as jointly owned assets of local residents.<ref name="井田" />

Some hot spring areas also feature {{ill|Day-use hot spring facility|ja|日帰り入浴施設|1=Day-trip bathing facility|1=Day-trip bathing facility|qq=draft|qq=draft}} with rest spaces attached.

