{{afc comment|{{ill|Sotoyu|ja|外湯|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

refers to communal baths outside lodging facilities shared by multiple users, {{ill|Uchiyu|ja|内湯|qq=draft|qq=draft}} denotes in-house hot spring baths privately installed within lodging facilities, and {{ill|Rotenburo|ja|露天風呂|1=Rotenburo|1=Rotenburo|qq=draft|qq=draft}} describes open-air baths typically without a roof or full enclosure.[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 01:41, 25 March 2025 (UTC)}}[[File:Dōgo Onsen.jpg|250px|thumb|{{ill|Dōgo Onsen|ja|道後温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}} Main Building ({{ill|Important Cultural Property (Japan)|ja|重要文化財|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)|2=ja|3=重要文化財|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq= (Japan)|4=ko|5=일본의_중요문화재|qq=draft|lt=Important Cultural Property|qq=draft}})}]]

'''Sotoyu''' (外湯) is one form of {{ill|Onsen|ja|温泉|1=Onsen|1=Onsen|lt=Onsen resources|lt_ja=温泉資源|qq=draft|qq=draft}} usage<ref name="高柳" />. It refers to a style in which a communal bathing facility (communal bath) is established collectively for use in a hot spring area (the source of the spring, or yumoto). Historically, such communal baths have also been called “motoyu” or “sōyu,” in addition to “Sotoyu.”<ref name="高柳">{{Cite journal |和書 |url=https://doi.org/10.6012/jwei.31.84|author=高柳友彦 |title=温泉資源管理の歴史 |journal=水資源・環境研究 |volume=31 |issue=2 |publisher=水資源・環境学会 |date=2018 |pages=84-87 |naid= |ref=}}</ref><ref name="益子">{{Cite journal |和書 |url=http://www.j-hss.org/journal/back_number/vol32_pdf/vol32no2_052_060.pdf|author=益子安 |title=温泉の集中管理 |journal=温泉科学 |volume=32 |issue=2 |publisher=日本温泉科学会 |date=1981 |pages=52-60 |naid= |ref=}}</ref> It is the counterpart to the {{ill|Uchiyu|ja|内湯|qq=draft|qq=draft}} that is typically set inside lodging facilities.<ref name="高柳" /><ref name="益子" />

== Overview ==
In combining Sotoyu and internal baths, there are four main patterns depending on the hot spring area: (1) establishing a central communal bath in the heart of the hot spring town; (2) setting up multiple baths at various hot spring sources located across the area; (3) a mix of communal and in-house facilities; or (4) places using only in-house baths.<ref name="高柳" />

In early modern hot spring areas (when water pumps did not yet exist), a low outflow volume of hot spring water made it inevitable to rely on communal use as Sotoyu.<ref name="高柳" /> From around the mid-early modern era onward, as shrine and temple pilgrimages became popular and roads were better maintained, {{ill|Tōji (hot spring therapy)#Tōji facility|ja|湯治#湯治場|lt=Tōji facility|lt_ja=湯治場|qq=draft|qq=draft}} sprang up in many regions.<ref name="高柳" /> However, not all lodging facilities at that time necessarily installed their own hot spring baths.<ref name="益子" />

During the early modern period, therapeutic bathing (tōji guests) was the main use of hot springs, making communal baths a social gathering spot for bathers and a symbol of the hot spring area.<ref name="高柳" /><ref name="益子" /> After the start of the Meiji era, however, with an increase in travelers for tourism and leisure, the use of in-house baths (internal baths) spread nationwide in Japan.<ref name="高柳" /><ref name="益子" />

In modern times and beyond, mechanical pumping of hot spring water began, resulting in major changes to how hot spring resources were utilized.<ref name="高柳" />

At {{ill|Asama Onsen|ja|浅間温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, for instance, both internal baths and communal baths (Sotoyu) existed as far back as the Edo period, and in the early Meiji period, the number of internal baths rose while communal baths also became more numerous.<ref name="井田">{{Cite journal |和書 |url=https://www.geoenv.tsukuba.ac.jp/~chicho/nenpo/7/08.pdf|author1=井田仁康 |author2=上野健一 |title=浅間温泉の形成過程と集落構造 |journal=地域調査報告 |volume= |issue= |publisher=筑波大学 |date=1985|pages=|naid= |ref=}}</ref> This led to the development of a system of “bath share certificates,” giving rise to three types of external communal baths: those used only by certificate holders, those open to general users upon payment of a bathing fee, and those managed as jointly owned assets of local residents.<ref name="井田" />

Some hot spring areas also feature {{ill|Day-use hot spring facility|ja|日帰り入浴施設|1=Day-trip bathing facility|1=Day-trip bathing facility|qq=draft|qq=draft}} with rest spaces attached.

